geom_col vs geom_bar

You can change the statistical transformation used by a geom with the stat argument…


carrier_counts &lt;- flights |&gt;
  count(carrier) |&gt; 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = carrier, y = n)) +
    geom_bar(stat = "identity")

Changing the stat argument

You can change the statistical transformation used by a geom with the stat argument…


carrier_counts &lt;- flights |&gt;
  count(carrier) |&gt; 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = carrier, y = n)) +
    geom_bar(stat = "identity")

Two Categorical Variables

To visualize the covariation between two categorical variables, count the number of observations for each combination.


diamonds |&gt;
  count(color, cut) |&gt;  
  ggplot(aes(x = color, y = cut)) +
  geom_tile(aes(fill = n))

fct_reorder()

Reorders a factor by another variable, useful for plots.
For example, ordering bars in a bar chart.


gss_cat |&gt;
  filter(rincome != "Not applicable") |&gt;
  group_by(rincome) |&gt;
  summarize(age = mean(age, na.rm = TRUE)) |&gt;
  mutate(rincome = fct_reorder(rincome, age)) |&gt;
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = rincome)) +
  geom_col()

fct_infreq()

Reorders a factor by the frequency of its values.


gss_cat |&gt;
  count(race) |&gt;
  mutate(race = fct_infreq(race)) |&gt; 
  ggplot(aes(x = n, y = race)) +
  geom_col()

fct_relevel()

Manually move levels to the front.


p1 &lt;- gss_cat |&gt; 
  ggplot(aes(x = partyid)) +
  geom_bar()

p2 &lt;- gss_cat |&gt; 
  mutate(partyid = fct_relevel(partyid, "Independent")) |&gt; 
  ggplot(aes(x = partyid)) +
  geom_bar()

p1 + p2

fct_lump_*()

fct_lump_n() and fct_lump_prop() lump together the least/most frequent levels into an “Other” category.


gss_cat |&gt;
  mutate(relig = fct_lump_n(relig, n = 5)) |&gt;
  ggplot(aes(y = relig)) +
  geom_bar()

